            <section aria-labelledby="cg-howto-heading" class="prose">
              <h2 id="cg-howto-heading">
                How this capital gains harvesting calculator works
              </h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for US investors who want to model
                <strong>tax‑gain harvesting</strong> (also called capital gains
                harvesting): deliberately realizing long‑term capital gains in
                low‑income years to raise cost basis and reduce future taxes.
              </p>

              <h3>Key assumptions and formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>1. Unrealized gain on full position</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Total gain} = \text{Current value} - \text{Cost
                  basis} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>2. Portion harvested</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Harvest fraction} = \frac{\text{Harvest %}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Amount sold} = \text{Current value} \times
                  \text{Harvest fraction} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Gain harvested} = \text{Total gain} \times
                  \text{Harvest fraction} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong
                    >3. 0% long‑term capital gains bracket room
                    (simplified)</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Room at 0\%} = \max\bigl(0,\ \text{Zero‑bracket
                  limit} - \text{Ordinary income}\bigr) \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>4. Tax this year</strong></p>
                <p>We split the harvested gain into:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \(\text{Gain at 0\%} = \min(\text{Gain harvested},
                    \text{Room at 0\%})\)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \(\text{Gain at positive rate} = \max(0, \text{Gain
                    harvested} - \text{Gain at 0\%})\)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  If you enter a custom long‑term capital gains rate \(r\),
                  then:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Tax now} = \text{Gain at positive rate} \times
                  \frac{r}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>5. Basis step‑up and future tax savings</strong></p>
                <p>\[ \text{Basis increase} = \text{Gain harvested} \]</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Future tax saved} = \text{Basis increase} \times
                  \frac{\text{Expected future LTCG rate}}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Net benefit} = \text{Future tax saved} - \text{Tax
                  now} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                The calculator uses approximate US federal
                <strong>long‑term capital gains brackets</strong> for 2024–2025
                based on your filing status. It does not model state taxes, the
                3.8% net investment income tax, phase‑outs, or interactions with
                credits and deductions.
              </p>

              <h3>Interpreting the results</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimated tax this year</strong> shows the federal tax
                  cost of harvesting the specified gain, assuming your inputs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>New cost basis</strong> assumes you immediately
                  repurchase the same investment at today’s price, effectively
                  locking in a higher basis.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Future tax saved</strong> is the tax you avoid later
                  if you eventually sell the entire position at the expected
                  future long‑term capital gains rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Net benefit</strong> compares the future savings to
                  the tax you pay now. A positive number suggests the harvest is
                  likely beneficial under your assumptions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>When capital gains harvesting can make sense</h2>
              <p>Capital gains harvesting is most powerful when you have:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Low‑income years</strong> (early retirement,
                  sabbatical, between jobs, student years).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Large unrealized gains</strong> in taxable accounts,
                  especially broad index funds or ETFs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Future years with higher expected income</strong>,
                  pushing you into higher capital gains brackets.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                In those years, you may be able to realize thousands of dollars
                of gains at a 0% or very low tax rate, permanently reducing the
                tax you’ll pay later.
              </p>

              <h3>Capital gains harvesting vs. tax‑loss harvesting</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Capital gains harvesting</strong> realizes
                  <em>gains</em> (often at 0%) to increase cost basis and reduce
                  future taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tax‑loss harvesting</strong> realizes
                  <em>losses</em> to offset gains and up to a limited amount of
                  ordinary income.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                They are complementary tools. In high‑income years, investors
                often focus on tax‑loss harvesting; in low‑income years, they
                may switch to capital gains harvesting.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips and caveats</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Wash sale rule:</strong> It applies to losses, not
                  gains. You can generally sell and immediately rebuy the same
                  security when harvesting gains, but always confirm current
                  rules.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Short‑term vs. long‑term:</strong> This calculator
                  assumes long‑term gains (held &gt; 1 year). Short‑term gains
                  are usually taxed at ordinary income rates and are not ideal
                  for harvesting.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Other tax effects:</strong> Higher income from
                  harvested gains can affect ACA subsidies, Social Security
                  taxation, college aid, and various credits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>State taxes:</strong> Many states tax capital gains as
                  ordinary income. This tool does not model state‑level effects.
